The paper deals with the development of an end-to-end latent fingerprint search system, which involves automated region of interest (ROI) cropping, latent image preprocessing, feature extraction, feature comparison, and outputting a candidate list. This involves computer vision (cs.CV) techniques for image processing and feature extraction, as well as machine learning (cs.LG) techniques for feature comparison. The paper also discusses the performance of the system in terms of quantitative evidential analysis, which falls under the category of information retrieval (cs.IR). Additionally, the paper deals with the issue of latent recognition in law enforcement and forensic agencies, which falls under the category of computer security and cryptography (cs.CR). Finally, the paper evaluates the system on multiple databases, which involves multimedia (cs.MM) techniques for handling large amounts of data.
